&lt;p&gt;Glimmerized’s greyscale has a hint of purplish-blue to it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;aside class=&quot;rss-only&quot;&gt; &lt;p&gt;Open the full post in your web browser to view the colour palette.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/aside&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Themes like &lt;a href=&quot;https://ethanschoonover.com/solarized/&quot;&gt;Solarized&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://draculatheme.com&quot;&gt;Dracula&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=&quot;https://sailorhg.github.io/fairyfloss/&quot;&gt;Fairyfloss&lt;/a&gt; taught me how nice it is to use colours you like when you spend all day looking at them. So I’m very happy to now use Glimmerized in my text editor, website, calendar, and to-do list — hopefully for a long time to come!&lt;/p&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title>Photo of the day</title><link>https://rosschurchley.com/2025/flowers-dragonfly-lotus/</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://rosschurchley.com/2025/flowers-dragonfly-lotus/</guid><pubDate>Mon, 31 Mar 2025 07:00:00 GMT</pubDate><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/_astro/src.DGQX_a4G_LDWLf.webp&quot; width=2288 height=1718 alt=A pink lotus flower floats on a green lily pad in still water. A dragonfly rests on a petal.&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;dl&gt;&lt;dt&gt;Taken&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dd&gt;2016-08-11&lt;/dd&gt;&lt;dt&gt;Location&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dd&gt;Canada / BC / Burnaby / Simon Fraser University&lt;/dd&gt;&lt;/dl&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title>Photo of the day</title><link>https://rosschurchley.com/2025/flowers-petunia-macro/</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://rosschurchley.com/2025/flowers-petunia-macro/</guid><pubDate>Sun, 30 Mar 2025 07:00:00 GMT</pubDate><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/_astro/src.BZOgZJnZ_27kuWb.webp&quot; width=3072 height=2304 alt=Close-up of a purple petunia with visible pollen and stamen in the center.&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;dl&gt;&lt;dt&gt;Taken&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dd&gt;2007-06-24&lt;/dd&gt;&lt;dt&gt;Location&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dd&gt;Canada / BC / Kamloops&lt;/dd&gt;&lt;/dl&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title>Photo of the day</title><link>https://rosschurchley.com/2025/birds-chicken/</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://rosschurchley.com/2025/birds-chicken/</guid><pubDate>Sat, 15 Mar 2025 07:00:00 GMT</pubDate><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/_astro/src.C1vRzfWa_ETTSD.webp&quot; width=6000 height=4000 alt=A closeup of a white chicken with a grumpy-looking glare on its face, with its wattles scrunched up and its comb askew. It is next to a green bush and shares its pen with a black chicken in the background.&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;dl&gt;&lt;dt&gt;Taken&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dd&gt;2020-08-07&lt;/dd&gt;&lt;dt&gt;Location&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dd&gt;Canada / BC / Kamloops / Barnhartvale&lt;/dd&gt;&lt;/dl&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title>Photo of the day</title><link>https://rosschurchley.com/2025/birds-pigeon-tilted-head/</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://rosschurchley.com/2025/birds-pigeon-tilted-head/</guid><pubDate>Fri, 14 Mar 2025 07:00:00 GMT</pubDate><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/_astro/src.2P3EiLaY_Z1AnLGp.webp&quot; width=6000 height=4000 alt=A photo looking up at a pigeon perched on a wooden railing, its head slightly tilted. The sky behind is bright white.&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;dl&gt;&lt;dt&gt;Taken&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dd&gt;2022-04-10&lt;/dd&gt;&lt;dt&gt;Location&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dd&gt;Canada / BC / Vancouver / River District&lt;/dd&gt;&lt;/dl&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title>The 300-character spike</title><link>https://rosschurchley.com/2025/tweet-lengths-revisited-for-bluesky/</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://rosschurchley.com/2025/tweet-lengths-revisited-for-bluesky/</guid><pubDate>Thu, 13 Mar 2025 07:00:00 GMT</pubDate><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/_astro/src.CZxenyY7_Z19i16Y.webp&quot; width=1600 height=900 alt=Lots of Bluesky butterfly logos arranged in a grid and fading in from top to bottom. The first row of seven butterflies are labeled 140; the second fourteen butterflies are labeled 280; the last two rows of 15 butterflies are labeled 300.&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://rosschurchley.com/2015/tweet-lengths/&quot;&gt;Ten years ago&lt;/a&gt;, I discovered that a disproportionate number of posts on Twitter had exactly 140 characters. &lt;a href=&quot;https://rosschurchley.com/2020/tweet-lengths-revisited/&quot;&gt;Five years ago&lt;/a&gt;, I found the spike had shifted to the new 280-character limit. Now, Twitter has imploded and lots of people have migrated to Bluesky — what does the post length distribution look like on the new platform?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr/&gt;
&lt;aside class=&quot;rss-only&quot;&gt; &lt;p&gt;Open the full post in your web browser to view this chart.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/aside&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Once again, we reproduce the spike approaching the character limit, with 300-character posts accounting for over half a percent of the entire dataset — more common than any other length greater than 50.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Once again, we also see the effects of bots: two bots are responsible for posting random strings of length 46 and 256 every few seconds, causing those lengths to be overrepresented.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But this might be my favourite of the charts I’ve made in this series. Take a close look at the 140 and 280 character marks: a larger-than-expected number of posts are exactly those lengths or slightly shorter. The curve abruptly reverts to its original course — an exponential decay curve — immediately after those milestones. That’s exactly the behaviour we expect (and observe!) when people compose posts that are a bit too long, then edit them down to fit within a character cap.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It’s entirely possible that these might be the &lt;em&gt;exact same&lt;/em&gt; spikes we saw in my last two charts in this series, if people are reposting their old tweets from yesteryear on Bluesky. But I suspect this is more likely evidence of people crafting messages to be cross-posted to multiple platforms, in which case they may be using tools that recommend smaller limits than those supported by Bluesky. Time will tell what hypothesis is right!&lt;/p&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title>Photo of the day</title><link>https://rosschurchley.com/2025/birds-in-the-hand/</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://rosschurchley.com/2025/birds-in-the-hand/</guid><pubDate>Thu, 13 Mar 2025 07:00:00 GMT</pubDate><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/_astro/src.DQ-hs6ER_tir0d.webp&quot; width=6000 height=4000 alt=A female red-winged blackbird eats birdseed from someone&apos;s hand. The focus is on the bird, with the background greenery out-of-focus and the person&apos;s body out of frame.&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;dl&gt;&lt;dt&gt;Taken&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dd&gt;2019-06-23&lt;/dd&gt;&lt;dt&gt;Location&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dd&gt;Canada / BC / Burnaby / Burnaby Lake&lt;/dd&gt;&lt;/dl&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title>Photo of the day</title><link>https://rosschurchley.com/2025/birds-cawing-crow/</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://rosschurchley.com/2025/birds-cawing-crow/</guid><pubDate>Wed, 12 Mar 2025 07:00:00 GMT</pubDate><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/_astro/src.DOY6XY7k_Z2eDVl7.webp&quot; width=5589 height=3726 alt=A crow with wings outstretched and beak open in the middle of a clear blue sky. A branch of the evergreen tree from which the crow launched itself is just visible at the edge of the frame.&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;dl&gt;&lt;dt&gt;Taken&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dd&gt;2022-05-21&lt;/dd&gt;&lt;dt&gt;Location&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dd&gt;Canada / BC / Richmond / West Dyke Trail&lt;/dd&gt;&lt;/dl&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title>Photo of the day<